        analysis:
          'Jane Eyre\'s insistence on her own independence and self-worth is the driving force of the novel and was radical for its time. From her childhood rebellion against the Reeds to her refusal to become Rochester\'s mistress and her rejection of St John Rivers\'s loveless proposal, Jane consistently chooses integrity over comfort. Bronte creates a heroine who refuses to be defined by her gender, her class, or her lack of beauty, insisting instead on her right to feel, to speak, and to be treated as an equal. The famous declaration "I am no bird; and no net ensnares me" encapsulates Jane\'s fierce resistance to any form of entrapment, whether social, romantic, or spiritual. Jane\'s independence is tested most severely when she discovers Bertha Mason\'s existence and must choose between her love for Rochester and her moral principles. Her decision to leave Thornfield, despite her anguish, demonstrates that self-respect is not merely a philosophical position but requires painful, concrete action. Bronte was writing at a time when women had virtually no legal or economic autonomy, and Jane\'s insistence on financial and emotional independence anticipates the feminist movements of later decades. The novel argues that true love can only exist between equals and that any relationship built on dependency or deception is inherently corrupt.'
